{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487390"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:09:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:09:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"338"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/338"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.42,0.07,0.34,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112116"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/338"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94181"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"1122"},{"type":"tags","id":"1170"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2282"},{"type":"tags","id":"2544"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5523"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5614"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36821"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42063"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43003"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44253"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45934"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112116","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112116"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man develops acute shortness of breath five days following open low anterior resection for rectal carcinoma. His postoperative recovery has been complicated by an acute kidney injury but has otherwise been uneventful. There is no associated central chest pain, nausea or vomiting. On examination, his pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/80mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, temperature 37.5\u00baC and SpO2 91% on room air. His chest is clear to auscultation with equal air entry bilaterally, and his abdomen is soft and non-tender. Bloods taken earlier that morning show a worsening creatinine level of 285 \u03bcmol/L (baseline 90; reference 50-120) and an eGFR of 18 ml/min (\u0026gt;90).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation, in this setting, to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Electrocardiogram","V/Q scan","Chest X-ray","CT pulmonary angiogram","Arterial blood gas"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst there are a number of causes of dyspnoea in the post-operative period, perhaps the most important to consider in this scenario is pulmonary embolism (PE).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient in this scenario is at high risk of developing PE. Risk factors include recent major (open abdominal) surgery; and active malignancy (rectal cancer). Elements of the patient\u0027s clinical presentation that should also alert the candidate to the possibility of PE include the acute onset shortness of breath; new tachycardia and desaturation on room air. The clear chest on auscultation points away from differential diagnoses such as atelectasis and hospital-acquired pneumonia. The absence of central chest pain, nausea and vomiting may also direct the candidate towards a diagnosis of PE; but note that this does not necessarily exclude cardiac ischaemia as a cause of his symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003EECG\u003C/strong\u003E can show characteristic findings of PE including sinus tachycardia or S1Q3T3, it does not confirm the diagnosis. It may help to exclude cardiac ischaemia as a cause of this patient\u0027s deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful initial investigation to exclude other causes of acute shortness of breath and desaturation in this setting e.g. atelectasis, pneumonia; but is neither sensitive nor specific for diagnosing PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth \u003Cstrong\u003EV/Q scan \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003ECT pulmonary angiogram \u003C/strong\u003Ecan accurately diagnose PE. \u003Cstrong\u003ECT pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended in patients with renal impairment due to the associated risk of contrast-induced nephropathy. However, it may be considered if there was an ability to pre and post hydrate in a patient with a low but stable eGFR (as opposed to acutely low eGFR). In this clinical scenario, there is evidence of new renal impairment. Hence, \u003Cstrong\u003EV/Q scan\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate diagnostic imaging modality in the first instance. Note however that a V/Q scan performed in a post-operative patient can also be impacted by poor ventilation in the setting of factors such as atelectasis and pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArterial blood gas\u003C/strong\u003E can demonstrate abnormal respiratory or metabolic changes (in the setting of PE will be respiratory alkalosis) but does not confirm the diagnosis of PE. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["V/Q scan is preferred over CTPA in patients with severe renal impairment in the diagnosis of pulmonary embolism due to the associated risk of contrast-induced nephropathy."],"references":["Skinner S. Pulmonary embolism: assessment and imaging. Aust Fam Physician. 2013;42(9):628-32. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2013/september/pulmonary-embolism/","The Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Radiologists. Iodinated contrast media guideline. Sydney: RANZCR; 2016. Available at: https://www.ranzcr.com/college/document-library/iodinated-contrast-media-guideline","Worsley DF, Alavi A, Aronchick JM, Chen JT, Greenspan RH, Ravin CE. Chest radiographic findings in patients with acute pulmonary embolism: observations from the PIOPED Study. Radiology. 1993;189(1):133-6. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/8372182/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94181"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"338"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94181"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-25T07:54:50+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-25T07:55:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"338"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112116"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nu